description:
Root cause behind sum_list (fz-h8w) and the int|float seam in
fact_5: ListHead(list(1|2|3|4|5)) types as `any` instead of
`1|2|3|4|5` when the list's Descr has been intersected (via branch
narrowing).

## Symptom

In sum_list's per-spec view:

  sum_s2 [list(1|2|3|4|5)]
  block_envs[blk5]: Var(0) :: list(1|2|3|4|5) & list(any)
  blk5 Var(5) = ListHead(Var(0))
  ft.vars[Var(5)] = any   ← bug

ListHead should give `list_element_type(list(1|2|3|4|5) & list(any))`
= `(1|2|3|4|5) ∩ any` = `1|2|3|4|5`. Instead gives `any`.

## Why this matters

This pollutes everywhere lists are involved in narrow-typed code:

- Cont captures of `h` widen to `any`.
- `h + sum_result` then computes `numeric_result(any, int) = int | float`
  (introduces float into a no-float fixture).
- Cont specs widen across callsites.
- Halt-cont chain seams diverge.

This is the typer-side root cause of the cont-chain seam issue
filed as fz-h8w. Fix here likely dissolves the sum_list failure
without touching cont keying.

## Bug location

src/typer.rs line 70:

  pub fn list_element_type(scrut: &Descr) -> Descr {
      let mut elem = Descr::none();
      let mut found = false;
      for clause in &scrut.lists {
          for sig in &clause.pos {
              elem = elem.union(&sig.elem);  // ← unions all sigs
              found = true;
          }
      }
      if !found { Descr::any() } else { elem }
  }

`scrut.lists: Vec<Conj<ListSig>>`:
  - Outer Vec = UNION of clauses (alternatives).
  - Each `Conj.pos: Vec<ListSig>` = INTERSECTION of list signatures
    (all must hold).

The function blindly unions over both. For a Conj with multiple
pos sigs (e.g. `list(A) & list(B)`), it returns `elem_A ∪ elem_B`,
which is the element type of the UNION not the intersection.

For `list(int) & list(any)` (a common narrowing pattern):
  - Bug: returns `int ∪ any = any`.
  - Correct: returns `int ∩ any = int`.

## Fix

Two-level walk:

  fn list_element_type(scrut: &Descr) -> Descr {
      let mut elem = Descr::none();
      let mut found = false;
      for clause in &scrut.lists {
          // pos sigs are intersected.
          let mut clause_elem: Option<Descr> = None;
          for sig in &clause.pos {
              clause_elem = Some(match clause_elem {
                  None => sig.elem.clone(),
                  Some(prev) => prev.intersect(&sig.elem),
              });
          }
          if let Some(e) = clause_elem {
              elem = elem.union(&e);
              found = true;
          }
      }
      if !found { Descr::any() } else { elem }
  }

(Negative sigs in `clause.neg` represent exclusion; for v1, ignore
them or treat conservatively. Element types under exclusion are
hard to reason about and not load-bearing for sum_list.)

## Acceptance

1. sum_list_via_head_tail_recursion passes (returns 15).
2. fact_5's k_2 narrow spec no longer needs Tagged slot1 (h is
   typed as int, not any, when captured from a narrow-list spec).
3. No regression on the existing 452 tests.
4. The float introduction in `h + sum_result` disappears for
   pure-int fixtures; numeric_result(int, int) = int.

## Related

- fz-h8w (cont-chain seam) may still apply for genuinely
  polymorphic chains (e.g. closures with truly any-typed inputs).
- Similar bug likely exists in tuple/map extraction over
  intersected Descrs. Filing as separate ticket if confirmed.
